<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-09-15T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-09-15T21:00:00-05:00" n="284" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d284">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">721.23/65: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru (<persName type="from">Dearing</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-09-15T21:00:00-05:00">September
                                    15, 1932—9 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received September 15—8:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>167. Department’s 55, September 15, 12 A.M., just received. I am glad to
                            report I have followed exactly the lines indicated in these instructions
                            in my conversations here. While the Department’s message is stated to be
                            for my personal information I believe it will be advantageous to
                            communicate it orally and informally to Foreign Minister and will do so
                            unless Department deems it inexpedient.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dearing</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>